[3]
Date: Tue, 9 Aug 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Itar-Tass, 8 Aug 2005 [edited]
<http://www.itar-tass.com/eng/level2.html?NewsID=2300180&PageNum=0>


Ban on Russian poultry import won't harm producers: ministry
--------------------------------------------------
The ban on the import of poultry and poultry farming products from
Russia imposed by a number of countries will cause no negative
effects on domestic producers, for the sole reason the export of
these items from Russia is very insignificant, Agriculture Ministry
has told Prime-Tass.

The EU countries banned the import of poultry and related products
from Russia and Kazakhstan in the wake of the bird flu epidemic,
although they are not their importers. Azerbaijan, Ukraine,
Kyrgyzstan, Tajikistan and Hong Kong did so, too.

Cases of avian influenza have been registered in the Novosibirsk,
Omsk, Tomsk, and Tyumen Regions and the Altai Territory [of Russia].
The disease has not affected any humans so far.

Bird flu has been identified in the Pavlodar Region of Kazakhstan.

The Emergency Situations Ministry last week warned that the bird flu
may travel from Siberia to European Russia during the autumn
migration.

It is believed that the disease was brought to Siberia from China.

The Russian union of poultry producers has asked the government to
take urgent measures to prevent the spread of the virus.

The Russian poultry farming industry has been [growing steadily] for
the past few years, as domestic demand has soared and import quotas
restricted import.

According to the Poultry Producers Union's forecasts, this year's
production was to grow by 17 percent on the year to 1.4 million
tonnes.

