<promed@promedmail.org>

[Russia officially notified the OIE on 5 Aug 2005 that the avian
influenza virus type A from Novosibirsk (Southwest Siberia),
initially (24 Jul 2005) reported as H5, has been finally confirmed as
H5N1. The notification includes some statements which require
clarifications:

1. The affected species are reportedly chickens, turkeys, ducks and
geese. However, birds of 5 species have been destroyed. What was the
5th species involved?

2. "In localities where the infection has resulted in deaths of
birds, mortality since the beginning of the epizootic has not
exceeded 3.3 percent". Such low death rates, if applicable to
chickens, put in question the pathogenicity of the Russian AI strain
and its similarity to SE Asian strains. Clarification will help.

3. Reportedly, "the application of control measures has sharply
reduced mortality". It is not clear what control measures have
reduced mortality of AI-affected flocks.
- Mod.AS]
